So I've essentially been at Blue Book during the entirety of the pandemic.

00:02:35.960 --> 00:02:41.720
So I started at Blue Book about a couple of months before kind of lockdowns for COVID

00:02:41.720 --> 00:02:42.720
happened.

00:02:42.720 --> 00:02:47.080
So I've been essentially remote my entire time there.

00:02:47.080 --> 00:02:50.080
So I lead a team of two data scientists currently at Blue Book.

00:02:50.679 --> 00:02:54.199
We're a company of about 150 employees currently.

00:02:54.199 --> 00:02:58.479
So we're kind of billed as the Kelly Blue Book of healthcare.

00:02:58.479 --> 00:03:03.679
So if you think about that, we offer fair pricing and market pricing for different healthcare

00:03:03.679 --> 00:03:07.839
procedures within a particular market across the United States.

00:03:07.839 --> 00:03:12.399
If you think about it, we don't shop for healthcare the way that we shop for something like a

00:03:12.399 --> 00:03:16.100
washing machine or clothing.

00:03:16.100 --> 00:03:21.740
So really the mission of our company is to change the consumerism of healthcare and offer

00:03:21.740 --> 00:03:27.139
our clients, which are primarily employers, and we work primarily through brokers, if

00:03:27.139 --> 00:03:31.699
anyone's familiar with the healthcare space.

00:03:31.699 --> 00:03:38.139
But we offer kind of direct to employer benefits where people can actually shop for healthcare

00:03:38.139 --> 00:03:43.660
and save money if they go to a low cost, high quality facility in their area for what we

00:03:43.660 --> 00:03:45.339
call shoppable services.

00:03:45.580 --> 00:03:52.179
So things like colonoscopies and mammograms, something that's planned or elective is considered

00:03:52.179 --> 00:03:56.580
shoppable, sort of trauma and things like that, car accidents, that's not considered

00:03:56.580 --> 00:03:57.580
shoppable.

00:03:57.580 --> 00:04:00.539
So we don't really cover things like that.

00:04:00.539 --> 00:04:04.259
We do have price information for our clients.

00:04:04.259 --> 00:04:08.179
And as of last year, we actually went through a merger and acquisition.

00:04:08.179 --> 00:04:13.419
We purchased a company called Quantros located in Greenville, South Carolina.

00:04:13.500 --> 00:04:18.140
So we do have kind of a quality division of sorts now, which is very similar to what I

00:04:18.140 --> 00:04:20.339
did at my last job.

00:04:20.339 --> 00:04:30.579
So we provide algorithmic support for quality models for providers and hospitals for different

00:04:30.579 --> 00:04:37.500
kinds of procedures and patient outcomes across the spectrum of healthcare.

00:04:37.500 --> 00:04:40.940
So that's really a little bit about Blue Book.

00:04:40.940 --> 00:04:45.700
I'll give a little bit of information as to how I arrived here, and then we can kind

00:04:45.700 --> 00:04:48.700
of open it up to audience questions.

00:04:48.700 --> 00:04:53.380
So I'll try to make this short because my journey to getting to Blue Book was, I guess,

00:04:53.380 --> 00:04:55.739
a kind of a long one.

00:04:55.739 --> 00:05:00.459
I spent most of my life so far in academic research.

00:05:00.459 --> 00:05:05.820
That's beginning not to be true, but so I earned a PhD in 2005.

00:05:05.820 --> 00:05:13.179
And for 10 years after that, I mostly worked in academic research, primarily within basic

00:05:13.179 --> 00:05:17.700
science and drug discovery within type 2 diabetes.

00:05:17.700 --> 00:05:24.260
And I returned to Vanderbilt in 2011 to do a postdoctoral appointment, which was unusual

00:05:24.260 --> 00:05:27.940
to work for a while and then go back and do a postdoc.

00:05:27.940 --> 00:05:30.700
But I was really kind of having a hard time navigating my career.

00:05:30.700 --> 00:05:34.140
I didn't really know what I wanted to do specifically.

00:05:34.179 --> 00:05:39.779
I had kind of this idea that I wanted to be a principal scientist in pharma, but it wasn't

00:05:39.779 --> 00:05:40.779
really working out.

00:05:40.779 --> 00:05:44.579
I had a few job interviews that didn't really pan out.

00:05:44.579 --> 00:05:49.980
So ended up returning to Vanderbilt for a postdoc, and it was really kind of a watershed

00:05:49.980 --> 00:05:52.260
time of my life.

00:05:52.260 --> 00:05:56.380
I started sort of figuring out that I really liked programming.

00:05:56.380 --> 00:06:00.540
I had gotten away from mathematical modeling as a graduate student and really wanted to

00:06:00.540 --> 00:06:02.179
return to that.

00:06:02.220 --> 00:06:07.579
Started teaching myself R, also started teaching myself Python.

00:06:07.579 --> 00:06:15.339
At the time, kind of 2014, 2015, data science was actually just so very new.

00:06:15.339 --> 00:06:19.459
And everyone kind of in the national market was talking about big data and companies were

00:06:19.459 --> 00:06:21.100
hiring data science teams.

00:06:21.100 --> 00:06:29.980
So actually, I ended up sort of befriending, if you will, a startup company called Axial

00:06:30.019 --> 00:06:33.940
Healthcare, which was the first company I worked for.

00:06:33.940 --> 00:06:37.019
They were in an incubator at the time in Nashville.

00:06:37.019 --> 00:06:43.700
So the National Entrepreneur Center is the singular startup incubator in Nashville.

00:06:43.700 --> 00:06:45.500
And so I just got to know them.

00:06:45.500 --> 00:06:49.779
The chief science officer had actually come to Vanderbilt to do a career talk.

00:06:49.779 --> 00:06:54.779
And so I asked her if I could come and shadow the company periodically just to kind of see

00:06:54.779 --> 00:06:55.779
what they're doing.

00:06:55.779 --> 00:06:59.540
I wasn't really sure what I was going to get out of the experience.

00:07:00.100 --> 00:07:01.100
But I started doing that.

00:07:01.100 --> 00:07:04.619
And interestingly, they gave me access to their database, which at the time was Google

00:07:04.619 --> 00:07:05.619
BigQuery.

00:07:05.619 --> 00:07:11.220
I didn't know SQL at all, had never written a line of SQL in my life.

00:07:11.220 --> 00:07:14.899
So I did kind of some freelance work for them.

00:07:14.899 --> 00:07:19.179
It wasn't really anything extensive.

00:07:19.179 --> 00:07:23.140
They asked me to do a few case studies and make a few charts.

00:07:23.140 --> 00:07:27.619
And I found it really compelling that my work was kind of friend-centered.

00:07:27.700 --> 00:07:30.579
So they were pitching this to their potential clients like the next day.

00:07:30.579 --> 00:07:34.899
And I found that really invigorating, just kind of the speed of which they were moving.

00:07:34.899 --> 00:07:37.339
And it seemed very impactful.

00:07:37.339 --> 00:07:43.739
And so I ended up actually, like a few months later, it happened very quickly.

00:07:43.739 --> 00:07:50.059
They got a series B round of funding as a startup, and they were going to move offices.

00:07:50.059 --> 00:07:53.980
And I remember approaching them in the parking lot one night at like 1030.

00:07:53.980 --> 00:07:57.899
And I said, I don't want to be presumptuous, but I really like you guys.

00:07:57.899 --> 00:08:01.980
I would be interested in full-time work here if you're interested in that.

00:08:01.980 --> 00:08:03.700
And they just kind of shook their heads.

00:08:03.700 --> 00:08:06.899
There was like five people in the company at the time.

00:08:06.899 --> 00:08:11.940
And two weeks later, they offered me a full-time job as a data scientist.

00:08:11.940 --> 00:08:14.380
So that's really how I got into this field.

00:08:14.380 --> 00:08:19.140
It was really kind of self-taught for the most part.

00:08:19.140 --> 00:08:21.700
When I was in school, data science programs didn't exist.

00:08:21.700 --> 00:08:23.959
It kind of wasn't a thing.

00:08:23.959 --> 00:08:31.040
So I've really kind of forayed my academic experience and research experience into a

00:08:31.040 --> 00:08:33.080
data science role.

00:08:33.080 --> 00:08:37.760
About nine months after I started at Axial, I was promoted to director.

00:08:37.760 --> 00:08:42.440
And really, for no other reason than I was a really good individual contributor.

00:08:42.440 --> 00:08:46.140
And they liked me as an employee, and they needed somebody to lead the team.

00:08:46.140 --> 00:08:48.239
So I was kind of there.

00:08:48.239 --> 00:08:53.760
And ended up building a team of about five data scientists at Axial.

00:08:54.559 --> 00:08:56.159
And I have since rebranded to Wayspring.

00:08:56.159 --> 00:09:04.400
So if you notice some differences on my LinkedIn page, that company is now called Wayspring.

00:09:04.400 --> 00:09:06.960
But it was really a huge time of growth for me.

00:09:06.960 --> 00:09:12.640
I started thinking very differently about my role as a data scientist at a company.

00:09:12.640 --> 00:09:15.080
What is the value that I add?

00:09:15.080 --> 00:09:23.000
I really had kind of a mind shift in terms of how I viewed data science at a for-profit

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:28.159
company and how I viewed research at a for-profit company.

00:09:28.159 --> 00:09:32.679
So while I was at Axial, I ended up going through a six-month leadership program, which

00:09:32.679 --> 00:09:35.719
was kind of life-changing for me.

00:09:35.719 --> 00:09:38.159
Really started getting super involved in my community.

00:09:38.159 --> 00:09:41.080
I now co-organize the National Data Science Meetup.

00:09:41.080 --> 00:09:45.719
I've been doing that for about six years now.

00:09:45.719 --> 00:09:51.359
Also really just started doing a lot of volunteer work with local universities and also boot

00:09:51.440 --> 00:09:56.440
camps, just in terms of mock interviews and kind of helping students along the way.

00:09:56.440 --> 00:09:59.280
I think I personally struggled with my career early on.

00:09:59.280 --> 00:10:07.080
So I really get a lot of fulfillment from helping others within the community and sort

00:10:07.080 --> 00:10:11.599
of fostering data science within the Nashville market.

00:10:11.599 --> 00:10:16.039
So I do a ton of panels and speaking engagements and things like this.

00:10:16.039 --> 00:10:17.039
So I really enjoy that.

00:10:17.039 --> 00:10:19.719
I'm also an adjunct professor.

00:10:19.719 --> 00:10:22.159
That's, I guess, my side hustle.

00:10:22.159 --> 00:10:26.960
I've taught previously at Columbia State Community College and then at Lipscomb University within

00:10:26.960 --> 00:10:29.159
their data science program.

00:10:29.159 --> 00:10:34.640
And then as of last semester, I'm currently at Middle Tennessee State University teaching

00:10:34.640 --> 00:10:39.359
capstone research within their Data Science Institute undergraduate program.

00:10:39.359 --> 00:10:44.239
Okay, well, that's a little bit about me and how I got here.

00:10:44.239 --> 00:10:51.760
I guess I kind of missed that I did leave Axial in 2019, in December of 2019.

00:10:51.760 --> 00:10:55.640
It was really just time to transition out of that company.

00:10:55.640 --> 00:11:00.760
And I started actually back in an individual contributor role at Blue Book.

00:11:00.760 --> 00:11:04.320
So if anyone wants to know more about that, I'm happy to talk about that experience.

00:11:04.320 --> 00:11:11.159
But I was a data scientist doing really just a couple of different projects for the company

00:11:11.359 --> 00:11:17.239
for about a year, and then have been subsequently promoted back to director at Blue Book with

00:11:17.239 --> 00:11:18.239
a team of two.

00:11:18.239 --> 00:11:23.840
Okay, well, I've talked long enough, it's 10-11 minutes.

00:11:23.840 --> 00:11:28.919
So is there anyone who would like to discuss anything, wants to know about healthcare,

00:11:28.919 --> 00:11:34.520
my path, data science strategy, which is very close to my heart now?

00:11:34.520 --> 00:11:35.520
Anything at all?

00:11:35.520 --> 00:11:37.559
I'll kind of open it up now.

00:11:37.960 --> 00:11:41.679
Could I just press a little on clarifying the business model?

00:11:41.679 --> 00:11:46.200
So there is a question anonymously sort of about that, like, you know, how do y'all make

00:11:46.200 --> 00:11:47.479
money?

00:11:47.479 --> 00:11:53.520
But maybe paint a picture of like, how does a company usually procure, I don't know, healthcare

00:11:53.520 --> 00:11:57.559
solutions, and then what y'all offer that is different?

00:11:57.559 --> 00:12:04.479
Yeah, so let me give for those of you who might not be familiar too much with our healthcare

00:12:04.479 --> 00:12:06.679
system.

00:12:06.799 --> 00:12:12.599
So when you sign up for health insurance through an employer, there's really kind of two different

00:12:12.599 --> 00:12:14.440
flavors of that.

00:12:14.440 --> 00:12:20.440
So the company could be at risk for their health insurance or not at risk.

00:12:20.440 --> 00:12:24.679
And what that means is, so small companies typically aren't at risk, meaning there's

00:12:24.679 --> 00:12:30.520
not enough employee base to actually have a meaningful pool of money from your premiums

00:12:30.520 --> 00:12:33.840
in order to pay out for healthcare services.

00:12:33.840 --> 00:12:37.000
So those are typically more expensive plans.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:41.960
Now your larger companies like your Amazon, your Walmarts, like really big, like fortune

00:12:41.960 --> 00:12:48.640
500 1000 companies, those companies typically are at risk, meaning the the role of the payer

00:12:48.640 --> 00:12:52.479
is usually administrative in nature only.

00:12:52.479 --> 00:12:57.479
So basically, you pay your premiums, and those go into a pool of cash.

00:12:57.479 --> 00:13:03.440
And that that cash is used for your office visits or your preventative care or any surgeries

00:13:03.440 --> 00:13:04.599
that are needed.

00:13:04.599 --> 00:13:08.840
So I get this question a lot, like how does blue book make money?

00:13:08.840 --> 00:13:14.320
So companies who are at risk, they typically want to preserve that pool of money in a lot

00:13:14.320 --> 00:13:16.440
of ways.

00:13:16.440 --> 00:13:20.400
And the reason is because they they are essentially responsible for it.

00:13:20.400 --> 00:13:27.880
So it makes sense for their employees to actually go to a facility for their mammogram or their

00:13:27.880 --> 00:13:34.119
colonoscopy, that's quite a bit cheaper, but is actually similar quality to a more

00:13:34.119 --> 00:13:36.479
expensive facility, right.

00:13:36.479 --> 00:13:42.119
So if they're if the pool of cash, you're only paying, let's say $200 for your colonoscopy,

00:13:42.119 --> 00:13:49.640
versus $1,000, then the the company's actually made $800 or conserve $800, let's say.

00:13:49.640 --> 00:13:52.960
Now, that's, that's a very basic example.

00:13:52.960 --> 00:14:00.260
But that's the reason employers want to purchase our products is because they they save money

00:14:00.260 --> 00:14:05.119
and conserve healthcare dollars by using our product.

00:14:05.119 --> 00:14:12.159
So we pretty much exclusively contract with companies who are at risk for health insurance.

00:14:12.159 --> 00:14:16.559
Does that does that answer your question?

00:14:16.559 --> 00:14:19.599
I think it understood.

00:14:19.599 --> 00:14:25.320
And the work that you're doing within blue book, specifically, you know, how is data

00:14:25.320 --> 00:14:27.239
science playing a role?

00:14:27.239 --> 00:14:29.440
Okay, that's a great question.

00:14:29.440 --> 00:14:35.799
So we really kind of have, at least now after the acquisition, there's kind of two elements

00:14:35.799 --> 00:14:37.080
of our business.

00:14:37.080 --> 00:14:40.200
One is cost, the other is quality.

00:14:40.200 --> 00:14:43.580
So I'll start a little bit with the cost piece.

00:14:43.580 --> 00:14:51.380
So we do have an analytics team that is responsible for the strategy and algorithms behind what

00:14:51.380 --> 00:14:57.539
is a fair price, for example, within Nashville or New York City markets, or wherever across

00:14:57.539 --> 00:15:03.099
the United States, what should we expect people to pay for a colonoscopy?

00:15:03.099 --> 00:15:07.020
Like what would you expect to pay for a washing machine, right?

00:15:07.020 --> 00:15:11.059
Like a fair price might be $500 or something like that.

00:15:11.059 --> 00:15:15.700
We don't really know that for something like a healthcare procedure.

00:15:15.700 --> 00:15:21.020
So really, the goal of that team is to look at the cost of different procedures, kind

00:15:21.020 --> 00:15:27.059
of the spectrum and spread across colonoscopies that happen within that market and determine

00:15:27.059 --> 00:15:31.020
from that distribution, what is the fair price.

00:15:31.020 --> 00:15:34.859
So we have an analytics team that's responsible for that.

00:15:34.859 --> 00:15:42.020
And then kind of separate from that, we have, we offer information on our website, we break

00:15:42.020 --> 00:15:46.299
it down into what we call kind of the stoplight colors, right?

00:15:46.299 --> 00:15:47.299
Green, yellow, red.

00:15:47.299 --> 00:15:52.580
So is this facility high cost, you're going to be paying more than the market rates?

00:15:52.580 --> 00:15:53.580
Is it yellow?

00:15:53.580 --> 00:15:54.580
It's kind of in the middle.

00:15:54.580 --> 00:15:55.580
Is it green?

00:15:55.580 --> 00:15:57.380
Is it below market rate?

00:15:57.380 --> 00:16:00.380
That's a little bit where data science comes in.

00:16:00.380 --> 00:16:03.099
So it's actually another team that supports the model.

00:16:03.099 --> 00:16:11.460
But we have some effort around classifying facilities as green, yellow, or red.

00:16:11.460 --> 00:16:13.619
And a little bit more goes into it than cost.

00:16:13.619 --> 00:16:16.700
I can't give all the secret information.

00:16:16.700 --> 00:16:22.500
But we have classification models that actually do that on the cost side.

00:16:22.500 --> 00:16:25.700
So that's one example.

00:16:25.700 --> 00:16:31.940
An example on the quality side is around prediction of patient outcomes.

00:16:31.940 --> 00:16:39.380
So healthcare quality is a little bit of an abstract thing, I guess.

00:16:39.380 --> 00:16:43.539
You know, when you think about healthcare quality, there's no real accepted definition

00:16:43.539 --> 00:16:47.219
of what it means to have quality healthcare.

00:16:47.219 --> 00:16:49.739
There's a lot of guidance out there.

00:16:49.739 --> 00:16:54.460
I mean, this is something that's been around probably since the 60s.

00:16:54.700 --> 00:17:00.700
It's mostly guided by what's called the Donabedian model, which is a framework of how we measure

00:17:00.700 --> 00:17:05.060
healthcare quality within the system that we have.

00:17:05.060 --> 00:17:13.219
So many companies, including ours, take the approach, and including CMS as well.

00:17:13.219 --> 00:17:19.020
The government also takes the approach of health outcomes as being a major indicator

00:17:19.020 --> 00:17:20.219
for quality.

00:17:20.219 --> 00:17:22.979
So did the person have a pressure ulcer?

00:17:23.339 --> 00:17:26.380
Did the person get sepsis while they were in an inpatient stay?

00:17:26.380 --> 00:17:28.699
You know, things like that.

00:17:28.699 --> 00:17:37.900
So for specific patient outcomes, we support regression models surrounding really four

00:17:37.900 --> 00:17:43.660
main patient outcomes across many procedures.

00:17:43.660 --> 00:17:44.780
It's really very broad.

00:17:44.780 --> 00:17:51.219
At Axial, we had a large focus on drug addiction, mostly related to opioids.

00:17:51.339 --> 00:17:53.099
Blue Book really covers the spectrum.

00:17:53.099 --> 00:17:59.140
So we have four different patient outcomes that we model through regression models that

00:17:59.140 --> 00:18:08.420
basically says, essentially, do we expect through the regression models, would the person,

00:18:08.420 --> 00:18:14.739
based on their patient profile, their comorbidities, would they have expected to have a poor outcome

00:18:14.739 --> 00:18:20.099
in an inpatient stay versus did they actually have the outcome?

00:18:20.540 --> 00:18:26.939
The idea behind that is if the person actually didn't have the outcome, but they were expected

00:18:26.939 --> 00:18:32.380
to have it, then that gap is where really quality lies, because the assumption is that

00:18:32.380 --> 00:18:38.540
the provider or the facility made some sort of intervention that would have prevented

00:18:38.540 --> 00:18:41.260
an otherwise poor outcome.

00:18:41.260 --> 00:18:49.739
So those are the two examples that I can give where data science contributes to our business.

00:18:49.739 --> 00:18:51.140
I'll give one more example.

00:18:51.140 --> 00:18:56.500
So those two examples I gave, it's important to realize those are, that's information that

00:18:56.500 --> 00:18:59.420
goes to our products.

00:18:59.420 --> 00:19:04.500
We also have an effort around internal optimization.

00:19:04.500 --> 00:19:07.979
So it's around engagement of clients.

00:19:07.979 --> 00:19:14.979
So as you can well imagine, some of the biggest challenges that we have as a company is actually

00:19:14.979 --> 00:19:17.739
getting people to use the website.

00:19:17.739 --> 00:19:23.459
So it's actually getting the consumer to engage with us, log on, search for their particular

00:19:23.459 --> 00:19:24.739
healthcare procedure.

00:19:24.739 --> 00:19:28.380
So that's more difficult than you might think.

00:19:28.380 --> 00:19:37.260
So we have an ongoing effort to understand really kind of consumerism in terms of why

00:19:37.260 --> 00:19:43.739
do people use our website, who uses it, who doesn't use it, who interacts with the healthcare

00:19:43.739 --> 00:19:49.859
system and has Bluebook as an option, but doesn't go there and why don't they go there.

00:19:49.859 --> 00:19:56.380
And so really what I'm talking about is heavily related to retail, right?

00:19:56.380 --> 00:20:00.579
Why do people purchase certain things?

00:20:00.579 --> 00:20:05.839
So we have an ongoing effort to try to understand that data just in terms of who uses our product,

00:20:05.839 --> 00:20:11.560
why do they use it, how do they use it, and can we potentially intervene in some way to

00:20:11.560 --> 00:20:15.839
increase those numbers and actually save people more money.

00:20:15.839 --> 00:20:19.359
Very good.

00:20:19.359 --> 00:20:23.439
And Phil made a comment or comment and have question.

00:20:23.439 --> 00:20:27.599
Phil, I'll give you a chance to chime in.

