00:20:34.839 --> 00:20:37.079
Yeah, I was really interested in your introduction.

00:20:37.079 --> 00:20:43.760
You talked a little bit about a mindset change when you were in the transition between the

00:20:43.760 --> 00:20:44.760
organizations.

00:20:44.760 --> 00:20:49.239
I'm curious to understand kind of what that change was, what aspects changed.

00:20:49.239 --> 00:20:53.560
Yeah, gosh, I could talk about this for the next five hours actually.

00:20:53.560 --> 00:20:55.439
So I'll try to shorten it a little bit.

00:20:55.439 --> 00:21:04.640
So you know, most of my experience really until that point has been in an academic laboratory

00:21:04.719 --> 00:21:10.719
and, you know, the incentives and the work styles in that scenario are very different

00:21:10.719 --> 00:21:12.000
than a for-profit business.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:19.000
You have to think a little bit more strategically about things like time to market, you know,

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:23.079
adoptability, interpretability of the models.

00:21:23.079 --> 00:21:26.880
Like you don't really, I'm not saying you don't have to think about that in academia,

00:21:26.880 --> 00:21:33.439
but there was less of a focus there, let's say, as opposed to sort of a small startup

00:21:33.439 --> 00:21:34.479
business.

00:21:34.479 --> 00:21:43.079
So I was really kind of designing projects that were maybe medium to long-term projects.

00:21:43.079 --> 00:21:47.920
I was really had a very like data-first mindset in terms of like I'm presented with a business

00:21:47.920 --> 00:21:52.640
problem and I'm immediately thinking, what fancy model can I build?

00:21:52.640 --> 00:21:59.719
And I really had to kind of shift how I think about that because there really is, you know,

00:21:59.719 --> 00:22:08.880
a lot to consider around just business structure in terms of growth opportunities, market opportunities

00:22:08.880 --> 00:22:13.800
that you have to think about in order to be a good data scientist and have a really high

00:22:13.800 --> 00:22:16.479
functioning data science team.

00:22:16.479 --> 00:22:24.040
So I had to learn, and I made a lot of missteps honestly early on, but I really had to learn

00:22:24.040 --> 00:22:28.680
from a network of great mentors that I was able to build over time.

00:22:28.680 --> 00:22:37.040
Like how do I position myself, position my team strategically within a company to really

00:22:37.040 --> 00:22:41.319
let us be as effective as we can possibly be for the business?

00:22:41.319 --> 00:22:43.439
And that could mean a lot of things.

00:22:43.439 --> 00:22:49.719
I'm not trying to be too vague about it, but it could mean that I'm a little more deliberate

00:22:49.719 --> 00:22:56.920
around partnering with our account team, our sales team, our product team, sort of figuring

00:22:56.920 --> 00:23:00.079
out how do I work with these teams most effectively?

00:23:00.079 --> 00:23:02.599
What kinds of questions do I need to ask them?

00:23:02.599 --> 00:23:07.640
How do I speak the language of the business to get them to understand things like model

00:23:07.640 --> 00:23:13.880
performance and how does it bring risk to the business or not?

00:23:13.880 --> 00:23:18.680
So that's really what I'm talking about when I say that I had to really kind of shift my

00:23:18.680 --> 00:23:19.680
mindset a lot.

00:23:19.680 --> 00:23:21.760
I started reading a lot of business books.

00:23:21.760 --> 00:23:26.920
I started listening to a lot of products, data product podcasts.

00:23:26.920 --> 00:23:29.280
I actually have this one book, I'm rereading it.

00:23:29.280 --> 00:23:35.920
So it's McKinsey and Company's Valuation, Measuring and Managing the Value of Companies.

00:23:35.920 --> 00:23:41.400
Like this is not a data science book by any means, but I think it's a good example and

00:23:41.400 --> 00:23:48.280
what I really encourage data scientists to think about is really taking some time to

00:23:48.280 --> 00:23:52.599
study the business and understand what is your C-suite thinking?

00:23:52.599 --> 00:23:59.719
You know, if you feel misunderstood about kind of your team or what you bring to a business,

00:23:59.719 --> 00:24:03.920
then I think it's important to kind of start talking their language and sort of understanding

00:24:03.920 --> 00:24:06.160
where they're coming from.

00:24:06.160 --> 00:24:11.839
Something that's come up recently in terms of our own product strategy and business strategy

00:24:11.839 --> 00:24:18.199
as a data science team, I'm starting to think about, okay, the projects that we have currently,

00:24:18.199 --> 00:24:24.719
if we are in a growth time of the business, do any of these projects, can I specifically

00:24:24.719 --> 00:24:30.479
tie them to more revenue growth in the next six months, 12 months, whatever the time period

00:24:30.479 --> 00:24:33.319
might be, right?

00:24:33.319 --> 00:24:36.760
I think a good data science leader sort of thinks about those things.

00:24:36.760 --> 00:24:42.000
I mean, maybe it's my opinion, but I've really kind of come to that conclusion over the years

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:47.400
that no one really wants to geek out with me about the latest data science models except

00:24:47.400 --> 00:24:49.959
for my team, right?

00:24:49.959 --> 00:24:54.319
And so, you know, I have to kind of speak their language in a lot of ways, and I find

00:24:54.319 --> 00:24:55.319
it really interesting.

00:24:55.319 --> 00:25:06.040
I think, I think a lot about data science and bringing science to people to help people

00:25:06.040 --> 00:25:11.400
and what that means to a business and how do I communicate it.

00:25:11.400 --> 00:25:15.959
I just, I think it's something that's really misunderstood and even, you know, I don't

00:25:15.959 --> 00:25:18.400
get right a lot of times either.

00:25:18.400 --> 00:25:23.280
And so, I've just, I have found that to be a very compelling piece of my transition out

00:25:23.280 --> 00:25:24.280
of academia.

00:25:24.280 --> 00:25:25.280
Perfect.

