When I think of pharma companies for, you know, or there is some portion of healthcare

00:26:25.439 --> 00:26:30.040
industry where open source tools cannot be used because you need to have a liability

00:26:30.040 --> 00:26:36.880
or a tracking and also you need products like SAS or that can, you know, somebody takes

00:26:36.880 --> 00:26:38.560
the liability for it.

00:26:38.560 --> 00:26:40.079
So these are my two questions.

00:26:40.079 --> 00:26:45.359
I want to understand, you know, what were your previous metrics of success, first question.

00:26:45.359 --> 00:26:50.479
Second one is what is the boundary in healthcare industry for open source technologies to be

00:26:50.479 --> 00:26:51.479
utilized?

00:26:51.479 --> 00:26:52.680
Okay, great question.

00:26:52.680 --> 00:26:56.520
So I'll start with your second question first.

00:26:56.520 --> 00:27:01.680
So you know, it is, I would say, a concern.

00:27:01.680 --> 00:27:05.680
Certainly privacy and data security is a concern.

00:27:05.680 --> 00:27:11.160
I would say at my last company and this company too, we are open source focused.

00:27:11.160 --> 00:27:18.520
So we actually have hybrid deployments currently in both Python and R for data science.

00:27:18.520 --> 00:27:22.599
On our development side, we also have things written in Python.

00:27:22.599 --> 00:27:25.900
So that's obviously an open source tool.

00:27:25.900 --> 00:27:33.760
We currently have a hybrid also infrastructure between on prem and cloud.

00:27:33.839 --> 00:27:36.479
Bluebook's been around a little over a decade now.

00:27:36.479 --> 00:27:42.319
So really, at that time, building cloud infrastructure wasn't really what people did mostly because

00:27:42.319 --> 00:27:44.459
of security concerns.

00:27:44.459 --> 00:27:51.000
So we early on had clients who did not want their data to be in the cloud.

00:27:51.000 --> 00:28:01.680
And at the time, this isn't true now, but up until recently, Microsoft would not allow

00:28:01.680 --> 00:28:07.359
a specific time for data breach notifications to be had.

00:28:07.359 --> 00:28:12.319
So it was it was too long to actually satisfy our clients.

00:28:12.319 --> 00:28:18.239
So for reasons like that, you know, maybe we weren't able to utilize certain cloud infrastructure

00:28:18.239 --> 00:28:21.479
tools that we would have otherwise.

00:28:21.479 --> 00:28:27.599
But I would say for us, it's been not so much a question of open source tools, but more

00:28:27.599 --> 00:28:33.439
of like on prem versus cloud platforms as to where we could potentially go.

00:28:33.439 --> 00:28:38.839
Now, Axial actually started in a cloud infrastructure.

00:28:38.839 --> 00:28:40.920
So it was a little bit different at that company.

00:28:40.920 --> 00:28:45.560
We didn't really have the same problem sets that we have now.

00:28:45.560 --> 00:28:49.920
We just we just have different problems than we have, I guess.

00:28:49.920 --> 00:28:57.839
But really, most of our security concerns have been around data warehousing and storage.

00:28:57.839 --> 00:29:04.719
And also, I would add to that data retention policies that we have had to fulfill for certain

00:29:04.719 --> 00:29:07.319
clients around that.

00:29:07.319 --> 00:29:14.520
So I would say I have personally not experienced security problems with using some open source

00:29:14.520 --> 00:29:16.239
tooling.

00:29:16.239 --> 00:29:20.160
It's more been around the platforms that we have.

00:29:20.160 --> 00:29:25.000
Okay, I'll go to your second question now.

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:29.560
So measuring success and ROI for data science team.

00:29:29.560 --> 00:29:33.680
So I think this is a really interesting question.

00:29:33.680 --> 00:29:38.680
I'll give you some sense of how we I've done in the past, I do it now and then I'll sort

00:29:38.680 --> 00:29:42.199
of give my overall sense.

00:29:42.199 --> 00:29:49.640
So at Axial, we had a few different measures of success for the team, which were kind of

00:29:49.640 --> 00:29:50.640
interesting.

00:29:50.640 --> 00:29:53.000
I've never really seen anybody do this other than us.

00:29:53.000 --> 00:29:59.000
But we had one measure was conversion rate of projects.

00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:04.359
So we had a mindset, at least after the first couple years, it was we didn't really have

00:30:04.359 --> 00:30:07.479
any measures for a couple years that I was there.

00:30:07.479 --> 00:30:11.479
And then I developed some for the team in conjunction with my current leader at the

00:30:11.760 --> 00:30:12.760
time.

00:30:12.760 --> 00:30:15.319
So one of them was project conversion.

00:30:15.319 --> 00:30:21.599
So how many projects come to us and what percent is actually converted to an actual deployment.

00:30:21.599 --> 00:30:25.199
So our target was about 5%.

00:30:25.199 --> 00:30:27.640
And I know that sounds really low.

00:30:27.640 --> 00:30:32.239
But our idea was that we want to fail fast, we want to fail often, it's kind of like a

00:30:32.239 --> 00:30:34.160
drug discovery mentality.

00:30:34.160 --> 00:30:36.920
It's like if things aren't going to work, we want to know early on, and then we want

00:30:36.920 --> 00:30:39.239
to get rid of it.

00:30:39.239 --> 00:30:46.400
So we had a 5% project conversion to deployment rate targets.

00:30:46.400 --> 00:30:54.599
We also had targets around the number of specific models that we wanted in what we called our

00:30:54.599 --> 00:30:57.579
data science portfolio library.

00:30:57.579 --> 00:31:02.199
So they didn't necessarily have to be like really fancy machine learning things.

00:31:02.199 --> 00:31:07.560
A lot of them were kind of business logic sort of ranking models.

00:31:07.680 --> 00:31:10.800
We had sort of data science portfolio targets.

00:31:10.800 --> 00:31:13.760
I can't remember an actual number.

00:31:13.760 --> 00:31:14.760
I don't.

00:31:14.760 --> 00:31:19.640
Yeah, I can't remember the actual number, but that was one of the measures.

00:31:19.640 --> 00:31:26.959
And then secondly, was around like sort of product value.

00:31:26.959 --> 00:31:33.199
Could we pinpoint that our model went into the data products and it resulted in more

00:31:33.199 --> 00:31:41.599
clients contracting with us, or a greater revenue because we were able to kind of upsell

00:31:41.599 --> 00:31:46.640
a data product due to the fact that we had added another feature.

00:31:46.640 --> 00:31:50.079
So we had some financial targets around that.

00:31:50.079 --> 00:31:54.680
So that's kind of how we handled it at Axial.

00:31:54.680 --> 00:32:01.199
Bluebook's a little bit different in that I'm not really sure.

00:32:01.199 --> 00:32:05.680
You know, honestly, up until this point, we've only had a formalized data science team

00:32:05.680 --> 00:32:08.280
since September.

00:32:08.280 --> 00:32:15.239
When I worked at Bluebook, before the acquisition, I was the single data science person.

00:32:15.239 --> 00:32:20.520
And I worked actually on the engineering IT side.

00:32:20.520 --> 00:32:24.959
Now since September, we do have a formalized data science team.

00:32:24.959 --> 00:32:30.839
So I'm currently working on sort of success measures and kind of what that looks like.

00:32:30.839 --> 00:32:34.400
So I don't have a lot of specificity for you in my current role.

00:32:34.400 --> 00:32:42.800
But I can say that we do utilize the outcomes and key results strategy that is published

00:32:42.800 --> 00:32:45.119
in a book called Measure What Matters.

00:32:45.119 --> 00:32:48.319
I think the author is Dorr, I believe.

00:32:48.319 --> 00:32:52.800
If you've never read Measure What Matters, I would highly recommend it.

00:32:52.800 --> 00:32:59.680
I also posted on LinkedIn today, Katie Nuggets came out with part one top data science books

00:32:59.680 --> 00:33:00.680
ever published.

00:33:01.520 --> 00:33:02.520
Oh, that was really good.

00:33:02.520 --> 00:33:04.319
So I think somebody had mentioned in chat about book recommendations.

00:33:04.319 --> 00:33:08.880
I read books all the time, especially big business ones.

00:33:08.880 --> 00:33:11.839
So anyway, that was a side note.

00:33:11.839 --> 00:33:14.680
So we use the OKR method of planning.

00:33:14.680 --> 00:33:18.959
And so essentially, we plan objectives and key results.

00:33:18.959 --> 00:33:23.260
And we do this by quarter, we've done this since I've been at Bluebook.

00:33:23.260 --> 00:33:27.479
So we have targets that are set every quarter.

00:33:27.479 --> 00:33:32.439
So projects really only last three months in duration.

00:33:32.439 --> 00:33:36.640
Now you might be asking yourself, well, what if a model bill takes longer?

00:33:36.640 --> 00:33:38.719
I think we'll cross that bridge when we come there.

00:33:38.719 --> 00:33:42.599
We actually haven't experienced that yet.

00:33:42.599 --> 00:33:48.800
But we try to and I try to plan for both myself and my team to have projects that are really

00:33:48.800 --> 00:33:54.640
in no longer than three month increments in order to kind of keep things going and sort

00:33:54.640 --> 00:33:57.640
of satisfy the business.

00:33:57.640 --> 00:34:03.239
So I know that's not very specific in terms of ROI.

00:34:03.239 --> 00:34:09.399
I will kind of end this by saying I think that data science ROI is really just a difficult

00:34:09.399 --> 00:34:11.939
thing to measure at times.

00:34:11.939 --> 00:34:19.800
My point of view is that I believe data science is a little bit of a capital expense at times,

00:34:19.800 --> 00:34:25.320
it's a little bit of a luxury, especially for small businesses that are not specifically

00:34:25.320 --> 00:34:27.360
AI focused.

00:34:27.360 --> 00:34:33.199
And so I think sometimes you have to look at it as this is a team that's going to do

00:34:33.199 --> 00:34:37.320
high risk projects, they're going to do research, things are going to fail a lot.

00:34:37.320 --> 00:34:38.959
And that's okay.

00:34:38.959 --> 00:34:44.919
Because we're willing to invest the you know, whatever amount it is $300,000 $400,000 a

00:34:44.919 --> 00:34:49.520
year in personnel salary for our small team.

00:34:50.239 --> 00:34:56.199
And be able to absorb that cost in terms of what we potentially get out of the team in

00:34:56.199 --> 00:35:04.000
terms of algorithmic deployed solutions, or specific insights and research that are valuable

00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:05.000
to the business.

