00:36:16.479 --> 00:36:17.479
Thanks.

00:36:17.479 --> 00:36:18.479
Okay, great question.

00:36:18.479 --> 00:36:19.479
Um, okay.

00:36:19.479 --> 00:36:22.000
So do we get a lot of reporting requests?

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:27.320
I'm actually kind of no, we did it Axial, we got tons of them.

00:36:27.320 --> 00:36:32.239
At Bluebook, we do have a dedicated client reporting analytics team.

00:36:32.239 --> 00:36:38.560
And we've been pretty successful, I think about making sure that people know that that

00:36:39.239 --> 00:36:41.280
is the reporting structure at Bluebook.

00:36:41.280 --> 00:36:48.399
So if, if clients need customized reports, or if there's questions about ongoing deployed

00:36:48.399 --> 00:36:55.520
reports that are typically either in like Power BI, or I think some of them are actually

00:36:55.520 --> 00:37:00.679
still like Excel based type stuff, then it really kind of goes to that team.

00:37:00.679 --> 00:37:06.520
I will say that we do get a lot of ad hoc requests in terms of what I would what I would

00:37:06.520 --> 00:37:12.840
characterize as like pilot type work.

00:37:12.840 --> 00:37:17.239
And I typically fulfill that.

00:37:17.239 --> 00:37:26.439
However, I really do always advocate for sort of quick decisions in terms of like, do we

00:37:26.439 --> 00:37:29.879
do we know what we want the outcome of this pilot to be?

00:37:29.879 --> 00:37:33.199
If we don't, we have to define that.

00:37:33.199 --> 00:37:38.719
And if when we define it, we come back to the table and say, okay, it was a success

00:37:38.719 --> 00:37:39.719
or failure.

00:37:39.719 --> 00:37:41.760
If it was a failure, we move on.

00:37:41.760 --> 00:37:47.080
If it was a success, then we turn this into a more deliberate project.

00:37:47.080 --> 00:37:52.800
And we have a scalable deployment strategy for that pilot stuff.

00:37:52.800 --> 00:37:59.560
So that's really a big piece of my job is to, I don't want to say protect my team.

00:37:59.560 --> 00:38:00.840
But it's a little bit like that.

00:38:01.479 --> 00:38:06.280
It's basically like kind of keeping everyone on track and saying, okay, you know, we, we

00:38:06.280 --> 00:38:13.080
have to really think very clearly about what we're doing in terms of kind of one off work,

00:38:13.080 --> 00:38:17.840
because you can drown in it very rapidly, in terms of like, that's all you're doing

00:38:17.840 --> 00:38:18.840
all the time.

00:38:18.840 --> 00:38:24.520
So that's part of my job is to kind of be a little bit of a gatekeeper there.

00:38:24.520 --> 00:38:27.840
Let's see, given that there's so many data sources.

00:38:28.840 --> 00:38:33.479
Yeah, like I said, we don't really do reporting now.

00:38:33.479 --> 00:38:40.919
But we do have a lot of documentation that we support for the business in terms of methodology.

00:38:40.919 --> 00:38:46.159
So that's probably the most closely related thing to a report.

00:38:46.159 --> 00:38:53.439
We are documentation is currently just in like Pete static PDFs that get versions.

00:38:53.439 --> 00:38:56.919
We're also we're trying to think a little bit outside the box of how to do that a little

00:38:56.919 --> 00:39:04.320
more clearly, I brought up the idea of making TikTok videos of our methods.

00:39:04.320 --> 00:39:06.600
I don't know if that landed very well, I would love it.

00:39:06.600 --> 00:39:13.320
But you know, I just think, you know, clients, it can come across as kind of dry.

00:39:13.320 --> 00:39:18.320
I mean, let's be honest, sometimes data science and talking about an algorithm can be boring

00:39:18.320 --> 00:39:20.360
to a lot of people.

00:39:20.360 --> 00:39:26.320
And so I think anytime we can make it fun, accessible, think about different platforms

00:39:26.320 --> 00:39:31.360
in which we communicate methods and why we're doing things, I think is always good.

00:39:31.360 --> 00:39:37.199
Can I ask what is the calculus in your head when you get an ad hoc request?

00:39:37.199 --> 00:39:42.879
Like you said, you typically say yes, I'm just curious what your thought process is.

00:39:42.879 --> 00:39:51.199
Yeah, so when I typically it comes in the form of some some kind of already ongoing

00:39:51.199 --> 00:39:52.399
projects.

00:39:53.199 --> 00:40:00.719
Typically, the calculus is in my head is usually to I don't want to say push back, but I always

00:40:00.719 --> 00:40:08.399
make sure that we're all on the same page in terms of what the objective of the request.

00:40:08.399 --> 00:40:13.679
And that can typically get me to where I need to be just in terms of getting people to think

00:40:13.679 --> 00:40:16.080
about because clients ask for things all the time.

00:40:16.080 --> 00:40:21.320
I'm sure that you all experience this as well in your own roles.

00:40:21.719 --> 00:40:26.919
It's kind of a never ending battle for different requests, different numbers, this than the

00:40:26.919 --> 00:40:27.320
other.

00:40:27.320 --> 00:40:31.239
I think it's always important to kind of take a little bit of a deep breath and say, OK,

00:40:31.959 --> 00:40:34.520
do we understand why this person is asking this?

00:40:34.520 --> 00:40:39.320
Is there a deficiency potentially in our reporting structures or our product that's not meeting

00:40:39.320 --> 00:40:40.120
client needs?

00:40:40.120 --> 00:40:43.879
If so, we need to pencil that in and address it.

00:40:44.840 --> 00:40:51.639
Or is this someone who's trying to kind of get some free analytical work done, which

00:40:51.639 --> 00:40:52.360
happens, right?

00:40:53.320 --> 00:40:56.280
So that's kind of the calculus that goes on in my head.

00:40:56.280 --> 00:41:01.719
I mean, certainly working for a small business, you know, you're never really going to get

00:41:01.719 --> 00:41:04.360
away from ad hoc work, pilot work.

00:41:05.239 --> 00:41:10.679
I've read blogs before that a lot of companies, it's like death by a thousand pilot projects

00:41:10.679 --> 00:41:14.360
because everything's always a pilot and never really becomes like an actual product.

00:41:15.479 --> 00:41:18.520
You know, I've seen that happen periodically, for sure.

00:41:19.560 --> 00:41:24.280
So really, the calculus in my head is typically one of do we understand what the objective

00:41:24.280 --> 00:41:24.439
is?

00:41:24.439 --> 00:41:27.879
Does it fall in line with our current company objectives?

00:41:28.439 --> 00:41:35.159
Does it fall in line with our vision for what the data product actually does in the market

00:41:35.159 --> 00:41:36.040
that we sell to?

00:41:36.840 --> 00:41:38.520
So that's typically how I'm thinking.

00:41:41.000 --> 00:41:45.959
There is a list of anonymous questions that we should get to.

00:41:47.000 --> 00:41:49.239
First one, it was actually right out of the gate.

00:41:49.239 --> 00:41:51.639
So I'm very sorry that we're just getting to it now.

00:41:51.639 --> 00:41:54.199
I noticed that you have your MBTI on LinkedIn.

00:41:54.199 --> 00:41:58.120
Any tips for those with less common personality types in the workforce?

00:41:58.120 --> 00:41:59.479
I am an INTJ.

00:42:01.320 --> 00:42:01.560
Okay.

00:42:03.000 --> 00:42:06.840
You know, look, I know that the science behind it is kind of weak, but I'm a big fan of

00:42:06.840 --> 00:42:09.719
personality tests, particularly leading people.

00:42:09.719 --> 00:42:12.679
I think it's really important to understand the person, how they work.

00:42:13.959 --> 00:42:18.679
It's something that was also sort of brought up in kind of leadership training.

00:42:20.840 --> 00:42:26.760
Look, I think there's room for all different personality types within data science or any

00:42:26.760 --> 00:42:27.800
field for that matter.

00:42:27.800 --> 00:42:33.560
I think the important thing is to really understand your own value proposition.

00:42:33.560 --> 00:42:35.879
I think this kind of speaks to kind of branding.

00:42:36.600 --> 00:42:41.320
I get a lot of career questions and do a lot of career talks and panels and things like

00:42:41.320 --> 00:42:41.639
that.

00:42:41.639 --> 00:42:44.919
And I'm a big proponent of branding.

00:42:44.919 --> 00:42:50.760
I think it's important to get your GitHub together, you know, have your LinkedIn profile

00:42:50.760 --> 00:42:54.120
up to speed, put some time and curation there.

00:42:54.120 --> 00:42:58.600
So I think it's really important to kind of define for yourself, who are you?

00:42:58.600 --> 00:43:04.280
What do you offer to a data science team or to whomever kind of you work for?

00:43:05.959 --> 00:43:08.919
And I think there's room for all personality types.

00:43:08.919 --> 00:43:12.360
It's just, it's really up to you for you to define for yourself.

00:43:12.919 --> 00:43:20.360
How does that particular type, what benefits does it kind of play within the grand scheme

00:43:20.360 --> 00:43:23.159
of what you want to do or accomplish at a company?

00:43:27.560 --> 00:43:30.520
Any tips for working at a smaller company?

00:43:30.520 --> 00:43:34.679
How do you handle underperforming colleagues when there isn't a lot of space for error?

00:43:35.959 --> 00:43:37.000
That's a great question.

00:43:37.719 --> 00:43:42.520
Okay, well, my tip for working at a small company is like things move quickly.

00:43:42.520 --> 00:43:50.360
And to say that I'm a data scientist or even a director of data science is probably inaccurate.

00:43:51.399 --> 00:43:53.560
I have to do some product development.

00:43:53.560 --> 00:43:55.320
I have to do people influencing.

00:43:55.320 --> 00:43:57.159
I have to do C-suite influencing.

00:43:57.879 --> 00:43:59.399
I have to do some marketing.

00:44:00.360 --> 00:44:01.800
I have to talk with clients.

00:44:01.800 --> 00:44:03.000
I do that often, actually.

00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:05.560
I'm brought into methods discussions.

00:44:05.639 --> 00:44:07.879
So I have to be an account manager at times.

00:44:09.639 --> 00:44:11.399
So I think that's the key.

00:44:11.399 --> 00:44:15.479
Like, I think being successful in a data science role at a small company,

00:44:15.479 --> 00:44:20.600
or really any role for that matter, really requires you to think of yourself more broadly.

00:44:21.560 --> 00:44:23.560
I can make another book recommendation.

00:44:23.560 --> 00:44:26.360
It's called Range by David Epstein.

00:44:27.800 --> 00:44:28.840
Anybody read this?

00:44:28.840 --> 00:44:29.399
Any hands?

00:44:30.360 --> 00:44:31.639
Give me an emoji or something.

00:44:31.719 --> 00:44:33.080
I have half read it.

00:44:33.080 --> 00:44:33.639
I haven't finished it.

00:44:33.639 --> 00:44:34.199
Half read it.

00:44:34.199 --> 00:44:35.239
Okay, that's good enough.

00:44:36.280 --> 00:44:42.040
This is a really good book that also heavily changed my perspective of who I am,

00:44:43.239 --> 00:44:45.639
just as a scientist and kind of what I offer.

00:44:45.639 --> 00:44:53.719
So I think, you know, my biggest sort of thing at working at a small company,

00:44:53.719 --> 00:44:56.520
my biggest piece of advice is you have to be a generalist.

00:44:56.520 --> 00:44:57.959
You kind of have to wear a lot of hats.

00:44:57.959 --> 00:45:00.040
You have to sometimes put on your engineering hat.

00:45:00.040 --> 00:45:04.280
You have to sometimes put on your engineering hat, your DBA hat, your data science hats.

00:45:05.080 --> 00:45:07.879
And some people don't thrive in that environment, and that's okay.

00:45:10.199 --> 00:45:11.719
There was a second part to that question.

00:45:11.719 --> 00:45:12.199
I'm sorry.

00:45:12.199 --> 00:45:14.439
I got sidelined by my book recommendation.

00:45:14.439 --> 00:45:17.639
It was around underperformance.

00:45:17.639 --> 00:45:18.679
Oh, underperformance.

00:45:18.679 --> 00:45:20.439
Nowhere to hide in a startup.

00:45:21.159 --> 00:45:21.800
Yeah, that's true.

00:45:22.439 --> 00:45:26.439
You know, I think the biggest piece in working for a startup,

00:45:26.439 --> 00:45:28.439
and I think this is true across the board,

00:45:29.399 --> 00:45:38.040
but, you know, the thing is you really have to be comfortable with very open-ended work.

00:45:39.080 --> 00:45:43.159
And typically folks who are just starting out, who are pretty junior,

00:45:44.040 --> 00:45:45.479
they have a hard time with that.

00:45:46.600 --> 00:45:50.840
You know, someone gives me something to work on, and it's like super vague.

00:45:52.439 --> 00:45:53.719
You know, what am I going to do with that?

00:45:53.719 --> 00:45:56.280
I'm going to use my expertise to kind of figure it out.

00:45:56.280 --> 00:45:57.959
I'm going to consult Google.

00:45:58.040 --> 00:46:01.080
I mean, you know, I've heard me, I've seen memes about like

00:46:01.080 --> 00:46:04.199
the number one job skill is knowing how to Google properly.

00:46:04.199 --> 00:46:05.959
I think there's a lot of truth to that, right?

00:46:05.959 --> 00:46:09.879
So it's really being able to take like very little information

00:46:10.840 --> 00:46:14.760
and provide something back to the business that is meaningful.

00:46:15.879 --> 00:46:19.000
And I think junior folks have a really hard time with that.

00:46:19.000 --> 00:46:23.000
I think it's a very, I think for some people, it's a very innate skill.

00:46:23.000 --> 00:46:25.879
I think for others, it's something they have to develop over time.

00:46:25.879 --> 00:46:28.439
And then I think a third group of people never develop it.

00:46:29.239 --> 00:46:33.719
And so, you know, folks who are underperforming

00:46:33.719 --> 00:46:37.159
are typically folks who really can't handle work like that.

00:46:38.120 --> 00:46:42.600
And so the way that I approach that is typically through a training exercise.

00:46:42.600 --> 00:46:45.320
You know, I work with them, instead of telling them what to do,

00:46:45.320 --> 00:46:48.360
I say, what do you think the next step is?

00:46:48.360 --> 00:46:52.520
You know, can you write me a plan of what you're going to do

00:46:52.520 --> 00:46:55.719
in order to execute on this project?

00:46:55.719 --> 00:46:57.719
And can we kind of work through that together?

00:46:58.600 --> 00:47:02.199
There's not really a specific playbook per se for that.

00:47:03.879 --> 00:47:06.360
But one truth I've learned is that

00:47:06.360 --> 00:47:09.479
when you don't really know what to do in a project,

00:47:10.520 --> 00:47:12.360
the best thing to do is EDA.

00:47:12.360 --> 00:47:15.560
Start with exploratory data analysis, understand the data.

00:47:16.760 --> 00:47:20.520
Like for example, you know, in our engagement work,

00:47:21.639 --> 00:47:25.080
really the first question I had was,

00:47:25.080 --> 00:47:27.959
well, how many people use our website?

00:47:29.719 --> 00:47:31.479
I mean, just a basic question

00:47:32.199 --> 00:47:35.879
that maybe hadn't really been explored very deeply.

00:47:37.159 --> 00:47:40.199
But knowing those basic things about where we are now,

00:47:40.199 --> 00:47:43.719
and this is part of data science strategy or strategy with any team,

00:47:43.719 --> 00:47:46.120
like assessing where we are present day

00:47:46.919 --> 00:47:49.560
is always really that good first step

00:47:49.560 --> 00:47:52.040
when you really don't know what to do in a project.

00:47:52.040 --> 00:47:55.800
So that's how I sort of approach an underperformer.

00:47:57.479 --> 00:48:00.919
I think it also, it can't be sort of said enough,

00:48:00.919 --> 00:48:04.439
just basic communication, sort of understanding where they are,

00:48:04.439 --> 00:48:05.560
what are their goals.

00:48:06.520 --> 00:48:09.719
In my experience, people who have underperformed

00:48:11.239 --> 00:48:14.040
have typically ended up leaving on their own.

00:48:14.840 --> 00:48:19.000
And there's usually a, again, in my experience,

00:48:19.479 --> 00:48:23.719
an understanding mutually that it's just not a great fit

00:48:23.719 --> 00:48:25.000
for whatever reason.

00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:29.959
So it kind of typically works itself out in that way, honestly.

00:48:33.080 --> 00:48:34.760
There's a question from Sloan.

00:48:34.760 --> 00:48:37.639
I'll give you the opportunity to ask if you'd like or feel comfortable.

00:48:38.520 --> 00:48:40.439
Sure. Nice to meet you, Lindsay.

00:48:42.760 --> 00:48:45.479
I am fairly early in my career.

00:48:45.479 --> 00:48:48.439
I've got a couple of years of experience as a data scientist,

00:48:48.439 --> 00:48:52.840
and I think I could probably do some work on my personal brand.

00:48:52.840 --> 00:48:55.239
And so I wanted to ask if you have any suggestions

00:48:55.239 --> 00:48:58.439
on really how to build a brand when you're just starting out.

00:48:59.719 --> 00:49:01.479
Yeah. So that's a great question.

00:49:02.439 --> 00:49:03.719
I think there are a couple of things.

00:49:03.719 --> 00:49:06.840
And KD Nuggets, they actually published,

00:49:06.840 --> 00:49:08.600
I posted it on my LinkedIn.

00:49:09.239 --> 00:49:12.360
You can find it there or maybe just search their website.

00:49:12.360 --> 00:49:16.679
They gave a blog piece on how to build a portfolio.

00:49:17.560 --> 00:49:19.239
And I thought it was really good.

00:49:19.879 --> 00:49:23.719
They basically went through the different platforms that you could use.

00:49:23.719 --> 00:49:25.879
So what are the common ones?

00:49:25.879 --> 00:49:30.360
GitHub with your code and also probably Markdown to describe it.

00:49:31.080 --> 00:49:32.919
LinkedIn is a good platform.

00:49:32.919 --> 00:49:35.879
People sometimes use social media sites as platforms.

00:49:35.879 --> 00:49:39.320
So Facebook, Instagram, Twitter, even.

00:49:41.479 --> 00:49:45.479
So yes, somebody posted the link.

00:49:45.479 --> 00:49:46.439
That's exactly right.

00:49:46.439 --> 00:49:50.360
So I think choosing your platform and your medium

00:49:50.360 --> 00:49:53.239
is something that's important to do kind of early on.

00:49:53.239 --> 00:49:54.840
Some people build their own website

00:49:54.840 --> 00:49:57.080
or use something like WordPress or something like that.

00:49:59.080 --> 00:50:02.120
You know, really the biggest barrier I find with people starting out

00:50:02.120 --> 00:50:04.600
is they don't really have any content, right?

00:50:05.560 --> 00:50:09.479
To me, the number one best way is to actually volunteer

00:50:09.479 --> 00:50:11.399
for a meetup speaking engagement

00:50:11.399 --> 00:50:14.199
and get somebody to record you speaking

00:50:14.199 --> 00:50:17.719
and teaching a group of people something about your work.

00:50:18.439 --> 00:50:20.679
It doesn't have to be advanced.

00:50:22.600 --> 00:50:27.800
I have lots of videos on my LinkedIn of where I've had speaking engagements

00:50:27.800 --> 00:50:29.479
and really I just started out.

00:50:29.479 --> 00:50:32.360
I agreed to a meetup one day and they recorded it

00:50:32.360 --> 00:50:34.520
and I'm like, well, I'll put this on my LinkedIn.

00:50:35.320 --> 00:50:37.560
And it really just kind of snowballed from there.

00:50:37.560 --> 00:50:42.280
So it's always amazing to me how many people starting out

00:50:42.280 --> 00:50:46.040
don't really take those opportunities that are so easy to get

00:50:46.040 --> 00:50:49.639
in terms of speaking engagements and being in front of a crowd.

00:50:49.639 --> 00:50:54.120
I know that it can be intimidating, but really a lot of meetups

00:50:54.760 --> 00:50:57.399
and the ones in Nashville are the same.

00:50:58.360 --> 00:51:02.360
They're very much geared toward people who are new.

00:51:03.479 --> 00:51:05.719
They're very grassroots kind of efforts.

00:51:06.360 --> 00:51:09.320
And so they're very open and welcoming to anybody

00:51:09.320 --> 00:51:12.520
with any sort of skill level coming and talking about a topic

00:51:12.520 --> 00:51:14.600
or teaching the group about something.

00:51:14.600 --> 00:51:18.679
That's one of the easiest ways to start building content for your brand

00:51:18.679 --> 00:51:25.719
which is typically video or it can be text.

00:51:25.719 --> 00:51:29.560
I'd put some time thinking about your bio and LinkedIn and sort of that.

00:51:30.760 --> 00:51:33.320
Running a blog is the next best way.

00:51:34.040 --> 00:51:36.919
I have a small blog that I probably need to pay more attention to

00:51:36.919 --> 00:51:39.320
but really just putting something out there

00:51:40.199 --> 00:51:43.560
just in terms of like your point of view on a particular topic.

00:51:43.560 --> 00:51:44.840
It really could be anything.

00:51:46.280 --> 00:51:47.719
It could be data science strategy.

00:51:47.719 --> 00:51:48.600
It could be leadership.

00:51:48.600 --> 00:51:52.280
It could be from the point of view of someone who's very junior

00:51:52.280 --> 00:51:55.159
and how they're feeling about how they're being led.

00:51:55.159 --> 00:51:57.159
I've not really seen that perspective a lot

00:51:57.159 --> 00:51:58.760
and I think that would be really impactful.

00:52:00.679 --> 00:52:02.600
So those are a few different ways.

00:52:03.560 --> 00:52:08.520
I would also encourage you guys to also post on LinkedIn.

00:52:09.560 --> 00:52:12.600
The more that you can kind of post things and share content

00:52:13.320 --> 00:52:14.520
then the easier it gets.

00:52:15.159 --> 00:52:18.280
It just kind of exercises that muscle a little bit

00:52:18.280 --> 00:52:22.040
and people will like your content or they'll share it

00:52:22.040 --> 00:52:24.520
and it really just kind of gets the ball rolling.

00:52:24.520 --> 00:52:26.919
So those are my biggest pieces of advice.

00:52:26.919 --> 00:52:30.520
Just choose your platforms and then start building content

00:52:30.520 --> 00:52:32.840
and find kind of low barrier ways to do that.

00:52:34.360 --> 00:52:35.000
Thank you.

00:52:35.000 --> 00:52:38.360
I have not heard the meetup piece of advice before

00:52:38.360 --> 00:52:42.760
so that's a good nugget that I'll definitely hopefully use in the future.

00:52:43.320 --> 00:52:46.199
Yeah, I'm sure everyone's located different places

00:52:46.199 --> 00:52:51.159
and most every city, even smaller cities, even Knoxville,

00:52:51.159 --> 00:52:52.840
we have meetups here.

00:52:54.120 --> 00:52:58.600
So even if you're not in a place where there is a large tech meetup

00:53:00.520 --> 00:53:06.040
sort of scene, you can always find like Philadelphia or San Francisco

00:53:06.040 --> 00:53:07.479
or maybe Austin, Texas.

00:53:07.479 --> 00:53:11.239
Like they all have meetups that I'm sure you could reach out to organizers

00:53:11.239 --> 00:53:14.360
and I know from experience as an organizer,

00:53:14.360 --> 00:53:17.080
they're always very hungry to find presenters

00:53:17.959 --> 00:53:20.280
and so they'll pretty much always say yes.

00:53:21.560 --> 00:53:24.520
So it's very low barrier to entry.

00:53:25.879 --> 00:53:26.280
Thank you.

00:53:26.439 --> 00:53:30.840
There's a similar, somewhat similar question that was submitted anonymously.

00:53:30.840 --> 00:53:33.239
How do you get started with speaking engagements?

00:53:34.199 --> 00:53:39.000
Yeah, meetups to me are the best way, the number one way to get started.

00:53:39.879 --> 00:53:44.439
And then I know in Nashville, we have an annual analytics summit

00:53:45.239 --> 00:53:47.560
that it's mostly local people that come to

00:53:48.360 --> 00:53:51.879
and so you can apply, you can submit an abstract for a talk.

00:53:51.879 --> 00:53:53.719
You can submit an abstract for a talk.

00:53:55.800 --> 00:54:00.040
So just finding those kinds of different platforms

00:54:00.040 --> 00:54:04.439
where you can give a talk or you really can't discount

00:54:04.439 --> 00:54:06.679
and I know it's hard, it's hard starting out

00:54:06.679 --> 00:54:11.719
but if you really take the time to like volunteer yourself,

00:54:11.719 --> 00:54:13.399
people are always looking for help.

00:54:14.679 --> 00:54:18.280
And so it really just takes kind of like,

00:54:18.280 --> 00:54:22.840
tamping down the imposter syndrome and putting yourself out there

00:54:22.840 --> 00:54:24.679
and saying, I want to do this.

00:54:24.679 --> 00:54:29.159
I mean, you'd be surprised at how many wins you can really get

00:54:29.159 --> 00:54:31.639
by just raising your hand and saying, I'm available.

00:54:32.439 --> 00:54:34.120
I would love this opportunity.

00:54:34.120 --> 00:54:35.639
Do you have any opportunities?

00:54:35.639 --> 00:54:37.959
Yeah, the answer might be no sometimes and that's okay.

00:54:37.959 --> 00:54:39.239
You just move on to the next thing.

00:54:43.320 --> 00:54:44.199
There's a question.

00:54:44.280 --> 00:54:47.959
Any thoughts on sites like GoodRx

00:54:48.919 --> 00:54:51.399
which seems similar but for shopping for prescriptions?

00:54:52.919 --> 00:54:58.199
Yeah, so we currently do have a prescription product,

00:54:58.199 --> 00:55:01.159
an Rx product that's relatively new at Blue Book.

00:55:02.679 --> 00:55:06.120
So, I mean, my thoughts on GoodRx, I've used GoodRx

00:55:06.120 --> 00:55:08.919
so I liked it because I saved on my prescription.

00:55:11.159 --> 00:55:13.000
I don't know that I have any thoughts on it

00:55:13.159 --> 00:55:16.760
other than I have heard through the grapevine from pharmacy friends

00:55:16.760 --> 00:55:19.719
that they don't like it because I think administratively

00:55:19.719 --> 00:55:21.320
it's actually very difficult.

00:55:23.320 --> 00:55:29.800
But, you know, I think anytime you can use something to empower a patient

00:55:29.800 --> 00:55:32.280
and I think that's really why I like Blue Book.

00:55:32.280 --> 00:55:38.040
I think it's fair to say that our healthcare system is very broken.

00:55:38.199 --> 00:55:44.199
It's 20% of our entire GDP in the United States, which is nuts.

00:55:45.479 --> 00:55:48.679
Another book recommendation I can make is called An American Sickness.

00:55:50.360 --> 00:55:52.840
It's a book about the history of our healthcare system

00:55:52.840 --> 00:55:55.000
and how healthcare insurance actually came to be.

00:55:56.199 --> 00:55:58.360
And it really breaks down administratively

00:55:58.360 --> 00:56:02.199
how different entities within the healthcare landscape work.

00:56:02.199 --> 00:56:04.040
It's really, really interesting read.

00:56:04.040 --> 00:56:09.320
It's also frustrating because I actually read it right before I came to Blue Book.

00:56:09.320 --> 00:56:11.239
And one thing I really like about Blue Book

00:56:11.239 --> 00:56:14.199
is that we are really devoted to helping the patients.

00:56:15.800 --> 00:56:19.239
Our products and services are very patient-centric

00:56:19.239 --> 00:56:21.639
and go directly to the patients themselves.

00:56:23.000 --> 00:56:25.479
So I personally like that about the company.

00:56:27.159 --> 00:56:29.719
I think I like GoodRx because, again,

00:56:29.719 --> 00:56:32.840
it's really devoted to helping patients save money.

00:56:34.439 --> 00:56:38.600
I don't know that I would consider GoodRx a direct competitor of ours necessarily.

00:56:39.239 --> 00:56:42.919
I think we offer just a little bit something different than GoodRx.

00:56:45.000 --> 00:56:45.800
But I like it.

00:56:45.800 --> 00:56:46.760
That's my opinion.

00:56:49.560 --> 00:56:51.639
Question about regulatory things.

00:56:51.639 --> 00:56:53.560
When dealing with healthcare patient data,

00:56:53.560 --> 00:56:56.360
how do you ensure the backend infrastructure is compliant

00:56:56.360 --> 00:56:58.360
to use AWS or some other vendors?

00:56:59.320 --> 00:57:02.360
So our cloud pieces are on Azure.

00:57:03.320 --> 00:57:07.479
And we do go through what's called HITRUST and SOC certification.

00:57:09.479 --> 00:57:10.679
I actually don't know the...

00:57:11.800 --> 00:57:14.679
I think we've passed one of them and not the other so far.

00:57:14.679 --> 00:57:15.000
I don't know.

00:57:15.000 --> 00:57:16.679
It takes a really long time to get.

00:57:16.679 --> 00:57:25.159
So HITRUST and SOC are really the two biggest kind of compliance sort of checkboxes,

00:57:25.159 --> 00:57:26.199
I guess you might say,

00:57:26.199 --> 00:57:30.760
that a company like ours who's considered a third-party associate can kind of go through.

00:57:31.639 --> 00:57:32.760
A lot of people don't know this,

00:57:32.760 --> 00:57:36.360
but HIPAA does not provide any sort of guidance

00:57:36.360 --> 00:57:40.280
as to what specific security controls that you have to have in place.

00:57:40.280 --> 00:57:42.600
It just says that it has to be secure.

00:57:42.600 --> 00:57:43.159
And that's it.

00:57:44.199 --> 00:57:46.679
So a lot of people don't realize that.

00:57:46.679 --> 00:57:54.040
So HITRUST and SOC certifications were really created to kind of address some of those.

00:57:55.639 --> 00:58:00.520
Can we provide specificity around what needs to be in place

00:58:00.520 --> 00:58:02.760
in order to really say that we're secure?

00:58:04.120 --> 00:58:05.719
So we go that route.

00:58:05.719 --> 00:58:12.199
I mean, certainly both AWS and Azure have products in place

00:58:12.199 --> 00:58:14.919
that they sort of bill as HIPAA compliant,

00:58:14.919 --> 00:58:20.919
which really means that it has encryption or other types of controls in place

00:58:21.879 --> 00:58:27.239
that would benefit us in terms of having a data breach.

00:58:28.040 --> 00:58:30.439
So those are the types of things we do,

00:58:30.439 --> 00:58:34.600
and that's not different than any other healthcare IT company.

00:58:37.959 --> 00:58:40.360
I just want to be mindful of time.

00:58:40.360 --> 00:58:42.679
Do you have a few minutes or you have a hard time?

00:58:42.679 --> 00:58:44.439
I have until three o'clock.

00:58:45.479 --> 00:58:45.959
Very good.

00:58:48.600 --> 00:58:51.800
So I asked this question with caution,

00:58:51.800 --> 00:58:54.040
so it's anonymous question and you don't have to answer it.

00:58:54.199 --> 00:58:57.879
I say that because the Hangout is not supposed to be about RStudio products at all,

00:58:57.879 --> 00:58:59.159
but there is an anonymous question.

00:58:59.159 --> 00:59:01.719
How is Bluebook using RStudio?

00:59:01.719 --> 00:59:03.000
What tools are you utilizing?

00:59:03.560 --> 00:59:06.600
Feel free to be as general or a closed mouth as you'd like.

00:59:07.719 --> 00:59:08.280
Sure.

00:59:08.280 --> 00:59:09.719
So I'm a big fan of R.

00:59:10.760 --> 00:59:14.600
Right now we do have hybrid deployment and data science at Bluebook.

00:59:14.600 --> 00:59:16.600
So we have things in both Python and R.

00:59:17.239 --> 00:59:19.719
Of course, Python and R are not the only games in town,

00:59:19.719 --> 00:59:21.800
but I think that's mostly what people use.

00:59:21.959 --> 00:59:25.959
So our regression models for quality are currently scripted in R

00:59:26.520 --> 00:59:28.120
using the RMS package.

00:59:31.080 --> 00:59:35.560
We have kind of a, I don't know what you would really call it.

00:59:35.560 --> 00:59:40.600
To me, it's not what people would consider a true deployment

00:59:40.600 --> 00:59:45.000
because a lot of the stuff that we do is really batch in nature, right?

00:59:45.719 --> 00:59:49.159
And I think this is not talked enough about in the data science community

00:59:49.159 --> 00:59:56.520
that sometimes you really don't need like, you know, API calls

00:59:56.520 --> 01:00:01.000
and sort of, you know, there's no reason to build in kind of functionality

01:00:01.000 --> 01:00:03.560
in which a user would be selecting data

01:00:03.560 --> 01:00:05.800
and you would be doing predictions on the fly.

01:00:06.360 --> 01:00:07.959
Like we don't have that.

01:00:07.959 --> 01:00:09.719
We just don't have the business case for it.

01:00:09.719 --> 01:00:14.520
So we currently do have batch scripts that run on Spark

01:00:16.600 --> 01:00:18.040
for our regression models.

01:00:19.399 --> 01:00:26.199
And then we have deployments in Python for other types of algorithms.

01:00:26.199 --> 01:00:30.280
So what I mean by that is we have some basic statistics stuff.

01:00:31.639 --> 01:00:37.560
We have fuzzy matching for some of our data cleaning efforts

01:00:37.560 --> 01:00:39.080
that are scripted in Python.

01:00:40.360 --> 01:00:41.800
I support those myself.

01:00:41.800 --> 01:00:45.159
They run mostly through cron jobs on Linux servers.

01:00:45.959 --> 01:00:49.320
So that's kind of the landscape of deployment for the most part.

01:00:49.320 --> 01:00:50.679
I mean, it's more nuanced than that,

01:00:50.679 --> 01:00:52.520
but I would say that's most of what we do.

01:00:54.919 --> 01:01:01.639
You know, I think we use the fully paid kind of RStudio at Axial

01:01:01.639 --> 01:01:02.679
and we really liked it.

01:01:04.679 --> 01:01:06.439
And it was, again, sort of the same thing.

01:01:06.439 --> 01:01:09.239
We had batch scripts that ran once a month

01:01:09.239 --> 01:01:11.000
and they were kicked off manually.

01:01:11.000 --> 01:01:13.879
It wasn't like a scheduled job or anything like that.

01:01:14.840 --> 01:01:17.159
You know, I'm not as hardcore maybe as some people.

01:01:17.159 --> 01:01:19.719
Like, I think if the deployment scheme works

01:01:19.719 --> 01:01:24.199
and you have really appropriate QA and controls and things like that,

01:01:24.199 --> 01:01:25.959
I'm a big fan of logging as well.

01:01:25.959 --> 01:01:28.040
If those things are in place, I think it's fine.

01:01:30.360 --> 01:01:34.199
You know, again, like it doesn't have to be like this full-fledged

01:01:35.239 --> 01:01:40.600
sort of totally hands-off, entirely 100% automated scripting

01:01:40.600 --> 01:01:41.719
kind of modality.

01:01:42.040 --> 01:01:44.919
But that's how we use R currently at Bluebook

01:01:44.919 --> 01:01:46.439
and I don't really see that changing.

01:01:49.239 --> 01:01:49.879
Very good.

01:01:49.879 --> 01:01:56.120
So I want to end on a topic that has come up a lot at these Hangouts.

01:01:56.120 --> 01:01:59.000
And I thought of the question when you gave a previous answer.

01:01:59.000 --> 01:02:01.800
So you wake up one day and you say,

01:02:01.800 --> 01:02:04.040
I have to work with other functions.

01:02:04.040 --> 01:02:05.159
I'm a data scientist.

01:02:05.159 --> 01:02:07.879
These other functions are not data science teams.

01:02:08.439 --> 01:02:09.800
You know, I'm a data scientist.

01:02:09.800 --> 01:02:13.719
Data science teams need to work with product or engineering or the C-suite.

01:02:13.719 --> 01:02:16.120
Like, how do you go about doing that?

01:02:16.120 --> 01:02:18.840
Like, you just wake up and start doing it.

01:02:21.080 --> 01:02:22.199
It's a great question.

01:02:22.199 --> 01:02:25.399
I would say, well, no, you don't really just start up

01:02:25.399 --> 01:02:26.840
and wake up and start doing it.

01:02:27.560 --> 01:02:30.520
I would say there's really been two things I've done

01:02:32.120 --> 01:02:34.439
to sort of be that person.

01:02:35.399 --> 01:02:38.360
And one of them is find mentorship.

01:02:38.919 --> 01:02:45.239
I think that is an underrated thing.

01:02:45.239 --> 01:02:48.600
I think a lot of, I've mentored some college students

01:02:48.600 --> 01:02:51.560
and honestly, I feel like I've not really been very useful to them

01:02:51.560 --> 01:02:55.399
because I think college students and folks starting out

01:02:55.399 --> 01:02:57.560
really need a different flavor of mentorship.

01:02:58.439 --> 01:03:01.000
I think once you've been working for a few years at least,

01:03:01.000 --> 01:03:03.639
maybe up to five years, then you really start thinking,

01:03:03.639 --> 01:03:05.719
wow, I really need somebody I can lean on

01:03:05.719 --> 01:03:09.239
to talk about my problems essentially and give me advice.

01:03:10.120 --> 01:03:12.679
And so really through my leadership training

01:03:13.639 --> 01:03:16.120
and then really just my involvement in the community

01:03:16.120 --> 01:03:19.639
and talking to a few people or several people,

01:03:19.639 --> 01:03:22.040
I mean, it's really become apparent to me

01:03:22.040 --> 01:03:25.320
that having really strong mentorship is really key to that.

01:03:26.280 --> 01:03:29.800
So people can give you advice in terms of what mistakes

01:03:29.800 --> 01:03:31.080
that they've made in the past,

01:03:31.080 --> 01:03:33.239
how they've approached talking to the C-suite

01:03:33.239 --> 01:03:34.439
or whatever the case may be.

01:03:35.879 --> 01:03:38.360
I think one thing I've really learned in terms of leaders,

01:03:38.360 --> 01:03:41.320
it's not just C-suite, it's management that's above you.

01:03:42.600 --> 01:03:48.040
I think oftentimes they are more willing

01:03:48.040 --> 01:03:51.080
and wanting to talk to you and hear your ideas

01:03:51.080 --> 01:03:51.879
than you might think.

01:03:53.239 --> 01:03:55.000
I think there's sometimes a perception

01:03:55.000 --> 01:03:56.600
that they sort of live in this very,

01:03:57.879 --> 01:04:01.399
they're very mature and they've got all the answers

01:04:01.399 --> 01:04:03.639
and that's really almost never the case.

01:04:03.639 --> 01:04:05.479
I mean, I think in my experience,

01:04:06.040 --> 01:04:08.040
your leadership really does want to hear from you.

01:04:08.040 --> 01:04:11.320
And I think sometimes they don't really provide

01:04:11.320 --> 01:04:13.719
obvious ways for you to do that.

01:04:13.719 --> 01:04:19.399
And so I think it's really kind of an exercise

01:04:19.399 --> 01:04:21.320
and kind of taking it upon yourself

01:04:21.320 --> 01:04:26.040
to find those ways that you can interact with them

01:04:26.040 --> 01:04:28.439
and talk to them in kind of meaningful

01:04:28.439 --> 01:04:30.679
and sort of low stress environments.

01:04:31.239 --> 01:04:33.800
It could be taking them to lunch one day.

01:04:33.800 --> 01:04:36.679
I mean, I know we work in a mostly remote environment now,

01:04:36.679 --> 01:04:37.879
so that's a little bit harder,

01:04:38.439 --> 01:04:40.840
but just finding ways that you can connect with them

01:04:41.560 --> 01:04:42.679
I think is important.

01:04:43.639 --> 01:04:46.280
And your mentors can help you sort of figure out

01:04:46.280 --> 01:04:47.320
what those ways are.

01:04:48.840 --> 01:04:51.800
The second thing that I've done is I read.

01:04:53.159 --> 01:04:54.679
I read a lot of books.

01:04:55.320 --> 01:04:56.360
Yes, I'm one of those people

01:04:56.360 --> 01:04:58.840
who actually reads physical books still.

01:05:00.679 --> 01:05:02.679
I listen to a lot of podcasts.

01:05:04.280 --> 01:05:07.479
Actually, one of my favorite podcasts is Pivot.

01:05:08.199 --> 01:05:09.800
If anyone knows Scott Galloway,

01:05:09.800 --> 01:05:11.479
he's an economist at NYU.

01:05:11.479 --> 01:05:13.719
I'm a huge Scott Galloway fan,

01:05:13.719 --> 01:05:16.919
like probably unhealthy,

01:05:16.919 --> 01:05:19.399
but I love Scott Galloway

01:05:19.399 --> 01:05:21.560
and I listen to all of his podcasts

01:05:21.560 --> 01:05:24.520
and looks like Robert's with me in the fan club.

01:05:26.040 --> 01:05:30.040
And listening to just like business oriented things,

01:05:30.040 --> 01:05:31.639
I think has really helped me,

01:05:31.639 --> 01:05:34.360
again, talk about data science very differently.

01:05:34.919 --> 01:05:37.080
Instead of talking about the algorithm

01:05:37.080 --> 01:05:40.439
and I've interviewed a lot of data scientists over time, right?

01:05:40.439 --> 01:05:43.719
And not that this is necessarily a red flag,

01:05:43.719 --> 01:05:46.760
but 95% of the data science interviews that I have

01:05:47.560 --> 01:05:49.719
asks this person to tell me about a project

01:05:49.719 --> 01:05:52.439
and they immediately go into the R library

01:05:52.439 --> 01:05:54.919
or what package they use or the algorithm.

01:05:55.479 --> 01:05:57.080
I actually don't want to hear about that.

01:05:57.959 --> 01:05:59.239
I want to hear about

01:05:59.239 --> 01:06:01.479
what was the problem you were trying to solve?

01:06:01.479 --> 01:06:04.199
Why did you think a data science solution was appropriate?

01:06:04.199 --> 01:06:05.879
Did you consider another solution?

01:06:06.520 --> 01:06:09.080
Can you talk about it in terms of

01:06:09.080 --> 01:06:10.760
what's written in McKinsey's book

01:06:11.479 --> 01:06:14.919
as opposed to very scientific terms, right?

01:06:14.919 --> 01:06:17.159
That's typically what I'm looking for

01:06:17.159 --> 01:06:19.320
in very experienced high performers

01:06:20.040 --> 01:06:23.239
is that they talk about data science work very differently.

01:06:23.320 --> 01:06:25.159
So those are really the two things

01:06:25.159 --> 01:06:26.760
that I've done over time

01:06:26.760 --> 01:06:28.679
to kind of get me to this point

01:06:28.679 --> 01:06:30.199
and I'm still not there.

01:06:31.239 --> 01:06:33.560
I think it'll be a lifelong journey, quite frankly,

01:06:33.560 --> 01:06:36.760
but I think once you really start to

01:06:37.959 --> 01:06:40.520
understand the landscape of data science

01:06:40.520 --> 01:06:43.639
and how it fits into different size businesses,

01:06:45.399 --> 01:06:48.120
then I think there just gets to be

01:06:48.120 --> 01:06:50.040
this kind of turning point in your life.

01:06:50.040 --> 01:06:51.800
And I just personally,

01:06:51.879 --> 01:06:53.399
it's resonated with me.

01:06:53.399 --> 01:06:57.560
I've really enjoyed the prospect of

01:06:58.600 --> 01:07:02.360
making my science very real to a consumer.

01:07:02.360 --> 01:07:03.639
And I love that.

01:07:05.639 --> 01:07:07.479
Yeah, before we go,

01:07:07.479 --> 01:07:10.760
I'm going to hold you to a tangible piece of advice.

01:07:10.760 --> 01:07:13.399
So like, what is the, if you could think of it,

01:07:13.399 --> 01:07:17.080
the crawl, walk, run for like someone

01:07:17.080 --> 01:07:18.600
who's just starting out in their career

01:07:18.600 --> 01:07:21.719
to actually like get exposure with data science?

01:07:22.439 --> 01:07:24.600
Leadership or other functions,

01:07:24.600 --> 01:07:26.360
like, is it a weekly email

01:07:26.360 --> 01:07:29.479
or five minutes stand up once a week?

01:07:31.080 --> 01:07:32.120
Yeah, it's a great question.

01:07:32.760 --> 01:07:35.080
A couple of things I've done that have been successful

01:07:35.080 --> 01:07:37.479
are asked to go to meetings.

01:07:38.439 --> 01:07:40.840
So if you know that there's a standing leadership meeting,

01:07:41.560 --> 01:07:44.280
some of them, they might not want everybody in, right?

01:07:44.280 --> 01:07:46.199
But if there's some sort of like

01:07:47.719 --> 01:07:49.639
product focused meeting or,

01:07:49.639 --> 01:07:50.679
I mean, you just get to know

01:07:50.679 --> 01:07:52.199
what happens at your company, right?

01:07:52.199 --> 01:07:54.280
So I think that's a really good way.

01:07:55.239 --> 01:07:59.399
It's a very low barrier way to get some of that exposure.

01:07:59.399 --> 01:08:01.479
I think anytime you can get exposure

01:08:01.479 --> 01:08:04.600
to what is discussed on other teams, it is a win.

01:08:05.320 --> 01:08:06.360
It does take time.

01:08:06.360 --> 01:08:07.639
It takes time out of your day,

01:08:09.320 --> 01:08:11.479
but it doesn't really affect the meeting.

01:08:11.479 --> 01:08:13.639
It doesn't affect the flow of business.

01:08:13.639 --> 01:08:16.759
And so just ask to sit in on stuff, right?

01:08:17.560 --> 01:08:20.279
Yeah, you might be told no for certain reasons.

01:08:20.439 --> 01:08:20.939
That's okay.

01:08:21.720 --> 01:08:25.000
But I think a lot of people will appreciate your willingness

01:08:25.879 --> 01:08:29.080
to really want to learn other aspects of the business.

01:08:29.080 --> 01:08:31.240
I mean, I have found that always to be true.

01:08:32.439 --> 01:08:35.240
That just me saying, hey, I want to learn more about this.

01:08:35.240 --> 01:08:37.479
Can I sit in on one of your meetings?

01:08:37.479 --> 01:08:39.560
Can I maybe sit in on a client call?

01:08:41.160 --> 01:08:44.040
I mean, I've always been told yes, 100% of the time.

01:08:44.040 --> 01:08:47.160
So that's a really easy way to do it.

01:08:47.879 --> 01:08:53.720
I think going to local meetups or networking events

01:08:53.720 --> 01:08:56.040
that are geared toward leader professionals,

01:08:56.919 --> 01:08:59.399
I think is another way to gain that exposure.

01:09:01.560 --> 01:09:03.959
Really just talking to people who do this kind of stuff.

01:09:05.160 --> 01:09:06.439
I have had less success

01:09:06.439 --> 01:09:08.600
with what's called informational interviews.

01:09:08.600 --> 01:09:11.879
So one of the career pieces of advice

01:09:11.879 --> 01:09:14.200
that I got early on was do an informational interview.

01:09:14.200 --> 01:09:15.959
Find somebody who has the job you want

01:09:16.520 --> 01:09:17.640
and reach out to them and say,

01:09:17.640 --> 01:09:19.479
hey, I would love to learn more about what you do.

01:09:20.040 --> 01:09:21.959
I've done that a handful of times.

01:09:22.600 --> 01:09:25.000
It's typically the people I've talked to

01:09:25.000 --> 01:09:26.759
have really kind of hated their jobs.

01:09:27.959 --> 01:09:30.200
So it never really worked out for me that good.

01:09:30.200 --> 01:09:33.959
But I do think it's still a good way to go.

01:09:33.959 --> 01:09:37.799
Like if you can, again, invite somebody for coffee,

01:09:37.799 --> 01:09:39.240
say, I would love to meet you

01:09:39.240 --> 01:09:40.520
and learn more about what you do.

01:09:40.520 --> 01:09:43.799
I mean, really, that's how I got my first startup job

01:09:43.799 --> 01:09:45.720
at Axial is I just reached out to them and say,

01:09:46.520 --> 01:09:48.520
like, I would love to come visit your company

01:09:48.520 --> 01:09:51.240
and just like be a little fly on the wall for the day.

01:09:51.240 --> 01:09:52.279
Are you willing to do that?

01:09:52.279 --> 01:09:53.080
And they said, yes.

01:09:54.120 --> 01:09:56.279
And so it completely snowballed

01:09:56.279 --> 01:09:59.399
into a professional networking relationship.

01:09:59.399 --> 01:10:02.120
So my biggest piece of advice is

01:10:02.759 --> 01:10:04.439
it really doesn't matter what you do.

01:10:04.439 --> 01:10:05.879
Just do something, right?

01:10:05.879 --> 01:10:07.000
Just take that first step.

01:10:07.000 --> 01:10:08.520
It doesn't have to be the right step.

01:10:09.080 --> 01:10:10.919
It doesn't have to be the right person.

01:10:12.839 --> 01:10:15.160
But do something to kind of kickstart that

01:10:15.160 --> 01:10:16.279
and do it regularly.

01:10:19.240 --> 01:10:20.279
That's my biggest advice.

01:10:20.279 --> 01:10:22.680
Very good, awesome stuff.

01:10:22.680 --> 01:10:25.240
So how can people get in touch with you

01:10:25.240 --> 01:10:26.120
if they would like to?

01:10:26.759 --> 01:10:29.080
Yeah, so the biggest way to get in touch with me

01:10:29.080 --> 01:10:30.200
is on LinkedIn.

01:10:30.200 --> 01:10:32.200
I'm on LinkedIn all the time.

01:10:33.240 --> 01:10:34.279
Have my phone app.

01:10:35.560 --> 01:10:37.240
I do just a lot of LinkedIn stuff.

01:10:37.240 --> 01:10:38.439
I learned a lot from LinkedIn.

01:10:38.439 --> 01:10:39.640
I follow influencers.

01:10:39.640 --> 01:10:41.479
I keep up with data science news that way.

01:10:41.479 --> 01:10:44.439
So I'm pleased, happy to connect

01:10:44.439 --> 01:10:45.879
with any of you on LinkedIn.

01:10:48.279 --> 01:10:50.040
I think my email is listed on there,

01:10:50.040 --> 01:10:51.959
but you can always message me on LinkedIn.

01:10:51.959 --> 01:10:54.279
I have the paid LinkedIn version or whatever.

01:10:54.279 --> 01:10:55.720
So you can drop me a note

01:10:56.439 --> 01:10:58.040
if you'd like my email or whatever.

01:10:58.040 --> 01:11:00.279
But that's absolutely the best way

01:11:00.279 --> 01:11:01.160
to get in touch with me.

01:11:03.399 --> 01:11:04.200
Very good.

01:11:04.200 --> 01:11:06.279
Well, thank you so much for the time.

01:11:06.279 --> 01:11:07.720
I don't know if you had an opportunity

01:11:07.720 --> 01:11:10.120
to look at all the comments in the chat.

01:11:10.680 --> 01:11:11.879
I did not see them.

01:11:11.879 --> 01:11:13.640
Yeah, everyone thought you were great.

01:11:13.640 --> 01:11:14.200
You really were.

01:11:14.919 --> 01:11:18.040
So thanks everyone for attending and sticking around.

01:11:18.040 --> 01:11:20.680
And Lindsay, I'm sure we'll be in touch next week.

01:11:20.680 --> 01:11:21.560
Rachel will be back.

01:11:21.560 --> 01:11:23.000
